An aside on statistical summaries

Ryan Hill

23 March 2019

The Data

We have 13 datasets, each with 142 datapoints with an x and y coordinate. We might want to quickly analyse this data, say get the mean and standard deviation of each dataset?

datasaurus_dozen %>% 
  group_by(dataset) %>%
  summarise(mnx = mean(x), 
            sdx = sd(x),
            mny = mean(y), 
            sdy = sd(y))
## # A tibble: 13 x 5
##    dataset      mnx   sdx   mny   sdy
##    <chr>      <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
##  1 away        54.3  16.8  47.8  26.9
##  2 bullseye    54.3  16.8  47.8  26.9
##  3 circle      54.3  16.8  47.8  26.9
##  4 dino        54.3  16.8  47.8  26.9
##  5 dots        54.3  16.8  47.8  26.9
##  6 h_lines     54.3  16.8  47.8  26.9
##  7 high_lines  54.3  16.8  47.8  26.9
##  8 slant_down  54.3  16.8  47.8  26.9
##  9 slant_up    54.3  16.8  47.8  26.9
## 10 star        54.3  16.8  47.8  26.9
## 11 v_lines     54.3  16.8  47.8  26.9
## 12 wide_lines  54.3  16.8  47.8  26.9
## 13 x_shape     54.3  16.8  47.8  26.9

Wow that’s amazing! All of our datasets have the exact same mean and standard deviation (to 2 decimal places anyway). We can even add in the correlation to see how well correlated the x and y are for each dataset:

datasaurus_dozen %>% 
  group_by(dataset) %>%
  summarise(cor = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 13 x 2
##    dataset        cor
##    <chr>        <dbl>
##  1 away       -0.0641
##  2 bullseye   -0.0686
##  3 circle     -0.0683
##  4 dino       -0.0645
##  5 dots       -0.0603
##  6 h_lines    -0.0617
##  7 high_lines -0.0685
##  8 slant_down -0.0690
##  9 slant_up   -0.0686
## 10 star       -0.0630
## 11 v_lines    -0.0694
## 12 wide_lines -0.0666
## 13 x_shape    -0.0656

Plotting the data

Okay so they seem pretty similar overall. But let’s plot the data and see just how similar they are…

It turns out they aren’t similar at all! All 13 of the datasets are completely different and show a completely different “relationship” to each other. This is why it’s always useful and important to visualize and understand the data rather than just blindly follow the numbers.
